segments.text: And as I say, my mission was we had to get that archaic system that they had turned into an automated system.
So having spent numerous hours in talking with Mr. Heaton about that, he said, well, look, I think what we need to do is create a new position.
and make you coordinator of our data processing operation.
So in 1967, well, they created that position and gave me that responsibility and hired a new assistant registrar and replaced me in the record section.
So I went to work then on further automating the record system.
And I wanted to do something about the registration system.
I wanted to get it where it wasn't such a chore for a student.
And I go back to my student day passport.

I used to say on that campus as a student, I can well remember, I had no idea at the time I'd ever be in that position, but I used to say two things if I ever had any authority around this institution up here that I would like to correct.
One of them was our registration system and the other was the fiscal office.

I it was just in any student of the era that I'm talking about would certainly agree with me because we just again I think it was just people who have been there and been there and they were not willing to change with the times and with all of the wonderful opportunities that we had with the computer aid being initiated in.
So we began to look at
improving the registration system, although we had to do it on the card system.
We then started going to a pre-registration system whereby a student would come in and visit with a counselor.
And I also felt very strongly about every student should have a counselor in the academic area that knew about the program that they were
pursuing and could sit down with them and have some valuable time and some counseling from the faculty members.
So Mr. Runner went along with that and they put in academic counselors who were professors or who were members of the faculty in departments and we began building this
the system that a student had at a contact point and that could start leading them toward a degree plan and that sort of thing.
So we developed the pre-registration system at that time and started it on the freshmen who were coming in in the summertime to try it out and then later passed it on to the entire student body.
Of course, that lasted for a while and then we felt like it needed to be upgraded even more and then went to another level.
I wanted, one of the things I wanted to do in my career there was to make registration absolutely as easy as it could be made.
And that later came true when I got in and got the touchstone registration system put in.
After I did that, I truly felt that my mission was completed.
All right now, so
The first major changes came in the late 60s?
Late 60s, early 70s, yeah, that's right.
And was it still key punch cards?
It was still key punch because they had no, we had no terminals or anything at that time.

All the data input was done by key punch cards and the student would go and register and then all this data would have to be taken to the computer center and key punch operators would punch this data in and build the student file and generate a sketch.
All right, let's see.
Mr. Heaton serves till when?
Mr. Heaton serves until 1972.
And Ed Cooper, this was under the Williams administration.
And Ed Cooper, who had been, as you well know, an assistant to Dr. Williams in the President's office for some years prior to that, was named our first Dean of Admissions and Records in 1972.
Well, I left a little bit of a gap.
After 1967,
In serving in this coordinator of data processing, I served in that for two years.
And one day Mr. Heaton called me in in 69, and I'm mistaken.
I need to stand corrected on what I said about Cooper's title.
Mr. Heaton called me in in early 69, and he said that Mr.
Rudder had talked with him and they were going to restructure the office.
And they made Mr. Heaton the first dean of admissions and records.
I've been corrected in what I said if I could be.
And they were going to make me registrar.
So I became registrar in February of 1969.
And Heaton was the dean of admissions and records.
All right.
Did your responsibilities change with the title change?
I had more responsibility, of course.
At that time, what did they do?
We started fanning out and increasing our staff because the enrollment was growing.
My job entailed, of course, the supervision of all of the student academic records, the residency, the assignment of classroom space.
One of the things that I insisted on when Mr.
Rudder wanted me to become registrar, and I had to talk to him about it.
Classroom space on the campus belonged, at least every department head thought, because they were in academic building, that they should teach all their classes in the academic building.
You've been through some of this.
And it was almost impossible to get any kind of respectable classroom utilization.
And so one of the things that I saw that one had to do to centralize that function, and if we were going to be responsible for it, then we needed to have the authority to assign.
So one of the things that I said to the president was that
I want to guarantee that the classroom space will be given, hopefully, to the registrar.
And that we will have total authority to assign the space.
And he agreed to do that.
And it made a lot of the faculty unhappy because they had to walk across campus to a class.
But our classroom utilization rose to the level of the best in the state, according to the coordinators.
Can you think of some anecdotes that exemplify some of the complaints?

Well, yeah, one that comes to mind immediately was, and we got ribbed for it for years, and I'm sorry I can't remember the department head that just happened then, but he was one that was very much opposed to leaving his building.
we have the authority to do it, well, we made an assignment for him to teach a class, and it just so turned out that we scheduled him in the men's restroom.
In his building.
In his building, and you can imagine the fun he had with that, and it lasted for a long, long time.
As a matter of fact, I think that was Dr. Clifford Sumane of the Capitol Engineering, I believe.
No, I'm Sumane.
No, I'm Sumane.
That's correct.
But...
There was a lot of complaining, but actually, I mean, they complained mainly because it was the inconvenience.
All of them knew in their hearts that the only way to have it done and have it done for it would be a good management tool was if somebody had to say, look, I have this room vacant over here.
It's just the size you need.
I'm sorry you don't have to walk across the way here to go to it.
But they knew in there.
I remember too, don't I, some complaints about faculty members not wanting a class except at the hour convenient to them.
That's correct.
That's correct.
And most of them wanted those from 8 to 12.
That's right.
And so that we expanded today.
The excellent point, I'd forgotten about that.
And most of them were on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from 8 to 12.
And so obviously one could see that that was not helping our utilization.
So we spread the day out and also started the Tuesday, Thursday hour and a half classes.
Do you remember how that change came about?
The Tuesday, Thursday?
Yeah, we dropped the Saturday.
It was in the mid-60s.
Yeah, yeah.
Was it the mid-60s?

Somewhere in the 60s, because Randy Mattson came as a prospective student, brought up here by Jack Knox and John Lindsey, and it was on a Saturday, and he wanted to meet some faculty members, and it was the first year we didn't have Saturday classes.
And they brought him over to Nagel Hall because Lindsey knew there were usually some history faculty over there hanging around.
And that's where I met him.
Garland Bayless was there.
And Randy and I still remember that Saturday.
I think it was 64 or 5, but I'm not sure.
It seems to me, I think it might have been after that, later than that.
Maybe not too much later, because it happened after I came over there.
I don't remember any complaints, do you?
No complaints, no.
And reason was that the students and the faculty both didn't have to look for Saturday in class or Saturday in form.
So I think everybody was very happy with it.
But the expanding of the day, the faculty member that wanted it at 8 o'clock in the morning now may be having to teach it at 2 in the afternoon.
That took a while for that to soak in or to get acceptance.
All right, let's go back now.
Cooper takes over in 72.
What was the search process, as far as you know?
I don't think there was a search process.
Did anybody contact you or anybody else?
No, no.
Dr. Williams...
just chose Ed Cooper to be the replacement for Lloyd.
I one day happened to have lunch with him.
And as we were going back, he asked me who I thought could do.
And I mentioned Cooper, and he quickly let me know that a lot of other people had mentioned Ed.
He was asking who would understand the campus student body, who would have credibility immediately.
and also who would be open in his communications with him.
And he'd already found Ed to be that way.
Now, did you know Ed well before?
Oh, I know him well, yes.
Dr. Williams' choice for Ed Cooper was an absolute excellent choice for the reasons you just named.
I mean, Ed was the job in admissions and records that is the toughest job
from a public relations standpoint, is admissions.
Records, you don't have that much.
Most of your work in public relations relating to records has to do with registration.
It has to do with transcripts.
And that was another thing that I wanted to improve there was an immediate transcript service.
I mean, I felt that students were entitled to get their transcripts as quickly as we could possibly get them out.
It hinged on getting in schools elsewhere.
It hinged on employment and things like that, and we owed them a very vast turnaround service.
And residency.
Residency was not a pleasant job at all because everybody wanted to be classified as a resident of Texas, simply for monetary reasons.
If you well remember, there was a significant difference between in-state tuition and non-resident tuition.
But admissions was getting tighter and tighter and tighter, thus making the job tougher and tougher and tougher.
You recall the time we went through our classroom space difficulties here, and we had to kind of curb the enrollment.
And Ed Cooper was a knack for that.
Ed was not a person that cared about any kind of controversy.
He didn't prefer that at all.
But he was such a PR person that he could sit down and assume most of the difficulty.
Share some examples of admission stories and anecdotes.
Gee.
Well, again, I wasn't directly involved with admissions that much.

I recall a lot of fun that Ed had with the old catalogs that had some admission requirements in there that you probably remember, and that one was that in order to enter A&M in the earlier years, you had to be
free of infectious diseases, and I don't think I have that all correctly.
And no felony convictions.
No felony convictions, and such things as that.
One of the things that helped us tremendously in admissions, if I recall correctly, was that in the years in the 70s and even up in the early 80s,
If a student didn't qualify, we had the probationary program that we could bring them in.

Ed was able to handle a lot of these cases that way where, you know, a student might not qualify and the parents were here and if they were former students, you know, I can't understand why my son or daughter can't get in school.
And rather than just say no, we had the program where, look, I'm willing, if you'll come here in the summertime, you might as well come at all.
The probationary program was a wonderful program to have.
Also, it said to the students, look, we haven't denied you.
If you can come here and do the work, make a C-outreach or whatever it is, then you have an opportunity to be a full-time student in the fall or the semester, whichever time you qualify.
So you're saying that was a good practice?
Excellent practice.
Do you have any guesstimate as to what percentage of the probationary admits made it?
Yes, I do.
About 60% made it.
Which...
May not seem to be that high, but on the other hand, they wouldn't have gotten it if we had just had a complete denial in the beginning and said, no, I'm sorry.
Now, as our admission requirements get stiffer and stiffer, did the former student complaints, did they increase in number also?
Yes, they did.
But it seems to me, if I recall correctly, Haskell, we still had the probationary program.
And it still gave us an opportunity to say to a student, hey, here it is, if you can do it.
And you see, when I left there in 1988, prior to that time, we were still doing that.
I don't know that that's available nowadays.
I don't know exactly what they're doing.
And then also the caps have come in since then.
Can you share any examples of apparent offers of bribes to get somebody in?
Did you ever hear of any?
Oh, yes.
I particularly had that.
I had that face me one time in particular.
I can remember very well who was up.
a gentleman from Washington, D.C.
He was a huge contractor up there.
As a matter of fact, he built the FBI building.
And he wanted his daughter into veterinary medicine school here.
And I was told, as we worked many times, that he had, this came from some former students, that the guy was coming and we needed to visit with him and whatnot.
And I did.
I think we even went to the country club and had dinner and whatnot, the usual thing.
And I told him from the beginning that there was just absolutely no way because you had to be a resident of Texas to get in our vet college.
And at the end of the conversation, he reached in his pocket and he said, I just need to know who to make it to and how much.
Not to me, he wasn't inferring it to me, but he was talking more or less about making a donation to the institution.
And I said, I'm sorry, we can't.
So you would get hints along like this from time to time.
And NM being the kind of school it is, and they wanted their son or daughter here, it happened, yes.
All right, under Ed, did any organizational changes occur?
Let's see.
You continued as the registrar?
I continued as registrar.
Now, what had happened was that we had employed a director of admissions.
As I mentioned to you earlier, when I came there in 1965, Mr. Heaton was both director of admissions and registrar.
Well, shortly after I had been there for, I think, a year or two, a couple years or whatever, then a director of admissions retired.
And when Ed came in, well, I think the fellow that had been there maybe had left, and that position was vacant.
It was vacant.
We hired Bill Lay at that time.
Now where did Bill come from?
Bill came from the public schools.
It seems to me that he was in Austin, I believe.
He might have been employed in
No, I don't think so.
He got his PhD from the University of Texas, but I don't think he was employed.
And this is in the early 70s?
This was in the 70s, that's right.
So Cooper, you, and Lay then are together for?
Well, let's see.
15 years?
Cooper left in 86.
86, okay.
86, and he came in 72 for 14 years.
That's correct.
And y'all move out of the Koch building over to the old Exchange Store building about when?
I think we moved, I believe we moved into the Exchange Store building about 1976.
Where did the idea of the name for that building, new name for that building come from?
The Heaton building?
I was the architect of that.
I felt like that Mr. Heaton had served the institution well and so there was a committee formed and we submitted it to the Board of Regents and they approved it.
Alright.
Now let's see.
So you didn't work for Rutter.
No.
Alright.
So it's Williams.
But you... No, you...
I didn't work for Williams, correct?
No, no, no, but I'm talking about during the time they were president.
Yeah, Rudder was president when you...
Rudder was president when I came, when I started in the registrar's office in 65.
Yeah, what... And then in 70... No, from your point of view, as a worker, as a registrar, describe Mr.
Rudder's style of leadership.
Well, Mr.
Rudder's style of leadership was very direct.
And, of course, you couldn't help but recognize a lot of that was due to his military experience.
Easy man to talk with.
Easy man to get in to see.
There were times when Mr. Heaton might not be available and he would want something and you'd go down and talk with him.
So I became very, very well acquainted with Mr. Glutter.
I liked his style.
I liked it because it was a lot like I am.
very, very direct.
You always knew where he stood type of administration and I think he had a great amount of respect for people that were doing their job and he recognized and he felt rather close to it.
Now, his key secretary was Nelda.
Nelda Ryle.
At that time.
Yes, and was she there
She was there just about the time he got there, wasn't she?
Almost all the time.
She worked for Dr. Graff.
She was Dr. Graff's secretary.
That's right, that's right.
And then moved in for another.
That's correct.
She was Dr. Graff's secretary when I was hired in 65.
She was there in the co-chair.
Describe her manner and style.
Wonderful, pleasant, all-business lady.
She was very, very valuable to any administrator because she knew
She knew the people very well that that administrator would have to deal with.
She was a good informant, so the administrator knew what to expect when that person came in.
She had a tremendous amount of background on everybody.
Who were the key people that Earl Rudder most trusted, if he needed advice?
Back in those days, Haskell,
And this is just my opinion, but I always felt that the president, particularly Mr. Rutter, he picked, I think, in my opinion, I'm correct, he basically handpicked his Board of Regents.
It's not the process that they go through today.
I know for a fact, because he told me from time to time,

make a list of who he wanted to be at that time they were called board of directors and it was just a matter of submitting that to the governor and generally he got the people he wanted so I would have to believe that he trusted his board greatly and you do remember the name of the governor during most of Mr.
Rudder's presidency that would be John B. Connolly who was a personal friend of General Rudder
And also, you're probably aware that he was personal friends with Lyndon Johnson, the President of the United States, of course.
I always felt, Haskell, that as a side comment to General Rudder, Texas A&M had General Rudder at the right time.
I had gone to school here, and our facilities were horrible.
In the classrooms, in the laboratories, it was bad, it really was.
There were a few areas that were all right, but generally speaking, facilities were not good at all.
General Rudder was here, and I've always thought that his friendship with John Connolly, the governor of Texas, and the president of the United States, he was able, A&M was not getting their share.
for what they needed out of Austin.
Our friends at the University of Texas were way ahead of us.
And I always felt that because of that relationship, General Rudder was able to get a lot of the monies lined up, although he didn't get to see all of the benefits those brought.
Dr. Williams, though, on the other hand, came in, and he was a man that sprung this up into the high recognition that this university
received or started to receive in the 70s.
But the funds were pouring in for what Rudder had set in place in our buildings and our facilities all certainly changed very quickly there.
And Jack Williams was right for A&M at the time he was here.
We were blessed with those two presidents in the town.
I agree.
I feel if we reverse the order, they both fail.
They're going to flunk.
Yeah.
But by having them as we did, it was just superb.
All right, but now on the staff, here on the campus, whom did Mr. Rutter listen to?
Mr. Rutter had a great amount of trust for Fred Benson, Dean of Engineering.
A great amount of trust for him.
Help me a little bit on business affair area.
Oh, thank you.
Tom Cherry.
He had a great amount.
Tom was in board with Trans World Airlines in New York, I believe, with the Vice President.
Yes, and he was able to lure Tom here.
Very, very...
Mr. Rutter hired Tom?
Mr. Rutter hired Tom, and Mr. Rutter also had a great amount of trust in Clark Diebel.
He brought him with him.
He brought Diebel here.
Diebel was in the land office with General Rutter when he was in Austin, and he trusted him very, very much.
Do you remember any...
Stories, allegations of fiscal mismanagement during those years?
Under Clark Neville?
Well, under Rutter.
I never heard of any.
I remember none.
Mr. Rutter had a great amount of trust in Clyde Freeman, who he knew Clyde and the president didn't always get along

about a lot of things sometimes, but Mr. Rutter trusted Mr. Freeman because he knew Mr. Freeman knew the state statute as though he had written it, and he knew he would keep him where he needed to be kept as far as the administration of any kind of funds or things like that.
And I think Mr. Rutter also was the man that brought Frank Huber here.
Yes.
Because if I'm not mistaken, Mr.
Rudder had said that he wanted the best school man, if not in Texas, in America.
And I think that he's the one that came up with one prank down at
My 7th grade band director, my 12th grade principal, and my superintendent.
He had also been in Austin when Mr.
Rudder had some Austin experiences, and I think they were well acquainted there.
Am I correct also that on campus matters, Mr.
Rudder sometimes would ask Ed Cooper a question about this or that?
Oh, very much so.
as far as Ed was his assistant, and Ed, again, back to what you said earlier that Jack Williams felt, Ed had a direct pipeline to the former students.
He knew so many of them.
And he had been to so many of their meetings and whatnot that he was able to go out and test the waters, I think, many times for the president.
And Ed was just a...
He was...
Everybody liked Ed, and everybody would talk to Ed.
And Ed spent a lot of time going around the campus and visiting with people.
So he was an excellent one to have out amongst the troops to get the sentiment of whatever the subject might be.
A goofy question pops in my brain.
Do you remember any old Army good bull?
